<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Simmondsia chinensis </i>is a rigid, many-branched shrub attaining a height of 2 m. The leaves are simple, evergreen, gray-green, and leathery. Its root system is extensive, often extending up to 10 m from the plant. Plants are dioecious, and pistillate plants develop nutlike capsules with one to three seeds. Small mammals collect and cache the seeds, which germinate following summer rains. Roots and stems sprout, and clones extend outward to form rings in old clones as seen in <i>Larrea tridentata. </i>Seeds are rich in oil that is used in foods, lubricants, waxes, disinfectants, and as a base for shampoos, creams, and ointments. It is cultivated extensively in many arid areas within and beyond California (Gentry 1958). </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Klein and Evens (2005) described a <i>Simmondsia chinensis-Eriogonum fasciculatum-Cylindropuntia californica</i> association in the Perris Valley (M262Bk) and Cahuilla Mountains (M262Bl) in southern California. Stands containing the species in Anza-Borrego State Desert Park (Keeker-Wolf 1998b), and Joshua Tree National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b, Keeler-Wolf et al. 2005) were included in other alliances, including <i>Eriogonum fasciculatum</i> and <i>Lycium andersonii</i> alliances, or they were identified as <i>Simmondsia chinensis</i> unique stands (Thomas et al. 2004). NVCS (NatureServe 2007a) has recognized a <i>Simmondsia chinensis</i> shrubland alliance in Arizona. We need further sampling and analysis to characterize the alliance in California. </div>
</div>

	

    
